[normal]Case of D[bold]D arrived as a child, had Discretionary Leave and applied in-time on form HPDL [Humanitarian Protection/Discretionary Leave, a
[normal] form which does not carry a fee] for an extension. Six years later the Home Office rejected his application as invalid. Solicitors wrote chasing letters and eventually a pre-action protocol letter to no avail and lodged an application for judicial review 
[normal]on the basis that their own policy said they were roughly five and three quarter years out of time to reject the application as invalid. The Home Office lodged summary grounds asserting that he should still re-apply because they were entitled to be paid a 
[normal]fee for the application because it should have been made on FLR (O) [Further Leave to Remain (Other) – form for which a fee is payable].  The case was listed for hearing.  It was argued that back in 2006 when the application was made there was no fee for t
[normal]he application that the Home Office said he should have made and they conceded before the hearing.  In that case costs were paid.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Case of R[bold]The application was rejected as invalid as invalid for use of the wrong form after more than three months.  The Hom
[normal]e Office website had directed the claimant to the form which the Home Office later said was invalid.  The Home Office did not back down until proceedings were issued.  They paid the claimants’ costs.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]R(S) v SSHD [bold][2011] EWHC 2120 (Admin)[bold] (05 August 2011) 
[normal]In this case the detention of a mentally ill man was found to be unlawful, in breach of Article 5 of, and to breach Article 3 of, the European Convention on human rights.  S was held in immigration detention at the end of his criminal sentence (all of whic
[normal]h he had served on remand).  Copious medical reports had been produced and he had been transferred to hospital. He was identified as a suicide risk and subject to hourly observations.  
[normal]Following a transfer to hospital a request for temporary admission was 
[normal]refused.  Judicial review proceedings were issued, a permission hearing was expedited. The judge observed “
[normal]Even Dr Ahmed's report of 24 June failed to lead UKBA to bring the matter to a resolution until another 5-6 weeks had passed and the order of this Co
[normal]urt had been obtained on 28 July…
[normal].In my judgment, the circumstances of S's detention passed the high threshold required for a violation of Article 3 and amounted to inhuman or degrading treatment. I find that there here was a breach of both the negative an
[normal]d positive aspects of Article 3”.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]R(HA) (Nigeria), v SSHD (Rev 1[bold]) [2012] EWHC 979 (Admin)[bold] (17 April 2012)
[normal]HA was also mentally ill and because of this was transferred to hospital.  Lawyers issued a judicial review challenging the lawfulness of his 
[normal]detention and asking for confirmation that he would not be transferred back to prison. No substantive response was provided before the application for judicial review was lodged on 28 October 2010.
[normal] Then came a letter maintaining detention and he was indeed
[normal] transferred back to detention. On 5 November On 15 December 2010 bail was granted unopposed. His detention from 
[normal]1 February to 5 July 2010 and from 5 November to 15 December 2010 was held to be in breach of Article 3 of the European Convention on
[normal] Human Rig
[normal]hts. The Judge held “
[normal]The length of time that it took to secure the Claimant's transfer to hospital between 1 February and 5 July 2010 was manifestly unreasonable and unlawful.”
