[normal]In the case below there was no order as to costs
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]F[bold]F was a young woman from Eritrea who had been recognised as a refugee.  The Local Authority stopped the support that had been provided to her as a Former Relevant Child under the Children (Leaving Care) 
[normal]Act 2000. – refugee status granted.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Her then legal 
[normal]representatives missed the deadline for judicial review. She had to drop out of education.  She applied for and got Job Seekers Allowance. She made what her current lawyers describes as “literally hundreds of job applications” but got nowhere as she had no
[normal] experience and English was not great.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] She wanted support from the Local Authority to start to study again and gain the skills to make her employable.  Her current legal representatives took on the case a year after the deadline for judicial review from t
[normal]he date her support stopped had passed, but arguing that the failure to support her was an “ongoing failure” and as such that deadline did not apply.  Permission was refused, but the application was renewed and succeeded.  The case was settled the case sho
[normal]rtly thereafter with no order as to costs on the basis that she got a very good package of support, greatly increasing her chances of employability in the future. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Her lawyer observes that although the underlying case was good the risks were high because 
[normal]of the delay and it would not be taken on if the proposed funding 
[normal]arrangmeents
[normal] came into force.
